WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.520
[Amit Varma]: What does it mean to be a citizen?

00:00:08.520 --> 00:00:11.920
[Amit Varma]: More specifically, what does it mean to be a citizen in a city?

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:14.520
[Amit Varma]: Here are some things that we know about India.

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:15.520
[Amit Varma]: 1.

00:00:15.520 --> 00:00:20.680
[Amit Varma]: India is more urban than we realize, and one day soon, most of India will live in its cities.

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:21.680
[Amit Varma]: 2.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:22.680
[Amit Varma]: This is a good thing.

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:24.960
[Amit Varma]: It's driven by the voluntary actions of people.

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:25.960
[Amit Varma]: 3.

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:30.480
[Amit Varma]: All our governance is centralized and nowhere near as local as it should be.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:31.480
[Amit Varma]: 4.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:35.680
[Amit Varma]: Even though our democracy has endured, there is a mismatch between power and accountability

00:00:35.680 --> 00:00:37.520
[Amit Varma]: at the local level.

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:38.520
[Amit Varma]: 5.

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:43.200
[Amit Varma]: Citizens in India are largely disempowered or at least feel disempowered, and the state

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:45.280
[Amit Varma]: is an imposing presence.

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:49.840
[Amit Varma]: All of these raise the question, if our system of governance is broken because of a flaw

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:53.320
[Amit Varma]: in our democracy, what can we do to fix it?

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:57.800
[Amit Varma]: Can citizens assert themselves and reclaim their rights?

00:00:57.800 --> 00:01:05.600
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:06.600
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.440
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:19.440
[Amit Varma]: A few months ago in episode 160, I had a stimulating conversation about participatory democracy

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:21.880
[Amit Varma]: with the polymath thinker Ashwin Mahesh.

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:26.360
[Amit Varma]: That was a hugely popular episode, and though it lasted around two and a half hours, it

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:27.800
[Amit Varma]: fell too short.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:32.440
[Amit Varma]: So I'm delighted to have Ashwin back on The Seen and the Unseen to chat about his thoughts

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:37.280
[Amit Varma]: on urban governance based on a paper and a presentation by him that will be linked from

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:38.280
[Amit Varma]: the show notes.

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:42.960
[Amit Varma]: Ashwin is in some ways a perfect guest for the show because I like to digress and take

00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:48.520
[Amit Varma]: the conversation into unexpected and different directions, and Ashwin's knowledge is both

00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:50.260
[Amit Varma]: wide and deep.

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:54.960
[Amit Varma]: So besides urban governance, we also chatted about the lockdown, how we should think about

00:01:54.960 --> 00:02:00.200
[Amit Varma]: education in an out-of-the-box way, and the responsibility, helplessness, and incentives

00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:01.200
[Amit Varma]: of citizens.

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:06.080
[Amit Varma]: As tends to happen, the conversation got more and more fun as we went along, and we argued

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:07.880
[Amit Varma]: a lot in the last part of the show.

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:11.260
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure there'll be much food for thought for everyone listening.

00:02:11.260 --> 00:02:16.860
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to the conversation though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:20.400
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Seen and the Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:21.680
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

