[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation.

00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:29.800
[Amit Varma]: Help keep this thing going.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:32.800
[Amit Varma]: Seenunseen.in slash support.

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:38.200
[Amit Varma]: Ashwin, welcome to The Seen and the Unseen yet again.

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:42.000
[Guest]: Well, my pleasure to be back, Amit.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, the episode that we recorded a few months ago, episode 160 on participatory

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:51.120
[Amit Varma]: democracy, which will be linked from the show notes, was actually incredibly popular.

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:53.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, people still keep writing in about that.

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:58.640
[Amit Varma]: And I did ask you a lot of questions about your personal journey in that episode, which

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:03.160
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to make you go through again, because we've already done that and listeners

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:04.320
[Amit Varma]: can listen to that.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:08.720
[Amit Varma]: But what I didn't explore in that episode was, you know, while we spoke about your career

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:15.320
[Amit Varma]: and your trajectory and how you, you know, got through the various interests and passions

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:19.760
[Amit Varma]: that brought you to where you are, we didn't speak one so much about your personal life.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:24.280
[Amit Varma]: And also, I'm interested in knowing, you know, how have you been through this lockdown?

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:25.280
[Amit Varma]: What's life been like?

00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:29.600
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about family, about home, about what you do in your downtime?

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:38.040
[Guest]: Well, I mean, I guess I'm not that different from millions of other people, both in terms

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:46.120
[Guest]: of regular home life and also in terms of how that has been impacted by the pandemic.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:54.240
[Guest]: I have two school going children, and therefore, there's a new rhythm that needs to be established

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:56.120
[Guest]: around that.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:05:03.880
[Guest]: It's fortunate that many of my kids' friends from school live in the community where I

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:04.880
[Guest]: live.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:11.960
[Guest]: So, in some sense, there is a semblance of continuity from the school environment.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:16.400
[Guest]: And it's also a small school, it doesn't have very many students.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:23.000
[Guest]: So in that sense, having a subset of kids in your own community, it's a larger subset

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.800
[Guest]: than it would be for any other school in some way, in percentage terms.

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:33.880
[Guest]: And so, I think they're managing okay, but they'd like to be able to go to school once

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:34.880
[Guest]: in a while.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:41.360
[Guest]: And the school even, I think, might allow occasional visits by parents just sort of

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:45.400
[Unknown]: for kids and parents to remember what the school is like and stuff like that.

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:50.400
[Guest]: But you know, on the whole, all of us have to be responsible through this pandemic.

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:55.840
[Guest]: And there's not a whole lot anyone seems to be able to do other than wait.

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:58.520
[Guest]: It's not always clear what one is waiting for.

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:02.560
[Guest]: But in a way, there's a lot of waiting, certainly.

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:09.360
[Guest]: Mostly, a combination of things that I do can still be done from home, whether it's

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:13.960
[Guest]: for Mapunity, or for India Together, or for any of the other things I'm involved in.

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:20.920
[Guest]: Obviously, the work at Lithium required a lot of hands-on work, but I've finally reached

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:26.760
[Guest]: the stage where that's probably best done by another set of professional people.

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:30.520
[Guest]: I'm thinking more and more about coming back to the public problem-solving things that

00:06:30.520 --> 00:06:32.800
[Guest]: interest me personally.

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:36.880
[Unknown]: And in that sense, the pandemic has given me an opportunity to think about how to reconnect

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:41.840
[Guest]: with some of the things that I haven't done as much of in the last couple of years.

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:45.920
[Guest]: A lot of the work in the last couple of years has been around the electric vehicles stuff

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:46.920
[Guest]: at Lithium.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:53.200
[Guest]: But I really have been wanting to get back to Mapunity in particular, and also my interest

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:54.600
[Guest]: in public interest media.

00:06:54.600 --> 00:07:01.440
[Guest]: And I think both of those decisions were in some ways accelerated by the time available

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:05.040
[Guest]: to think about these sorts of things in a pandemic.

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:10.480
[Guest]: And the municipal election is coming up here in Bangalore in, I don't know, in April.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:16.160
[Guest]: That's part of the things we'll talk about, not really clear how soon it will come up.

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:22.560
[Guest]: But that's another opportunity to sort of be part of and influence the thinking about

00:07:22.560 --> 00:07:28.120
[Guest]: governance in the city, public participation, things that have always interested me in the

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:30.880
[Guest]: last 10, 15 years.

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:38.640
[Guest]: So it's a nice pivotal moment in some ways.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:44.480
[Guest]: I think sort of at some level, the rest of it is, you know, one day at a time, trying

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:49.400
[Guest]: to see where all of this is going to lead and just responding to whatever happens in

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:50.400
[Guest]: some sense.

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:53.920
[Guest]: It's not really clear if tomorrow is going to bring more bad news or some semblance of

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:54.920
[Guest]: good news.

00:07:54.920 --> 00:08:03.400
[Guest]: Vaccines seem to come and go in the news, a little bit like oscillations on a sine curve.

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:07.160
[Guest]: So in a way, there's a lot of wait and watch.

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:15.480
[Guest]: Some of my family members got COVID and that was not something I was sort of mentally prepared

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:16.480
[Guest]: for.

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:21.360
[Guest]: And it takes you a while to sort of adjust to concerns like that.

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:25.720
[Unknown]: It's one of those things where you sort of know that things like fatality rates are very

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:31.760
[Guest]: low, but once you get it or someone close to you gets it, you tend to forget the other

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:36.120
[Guest]: 98 or 99% and imagine yourself in the 1 or 2%.

00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:37.760
[Guest]: And those are anxious things.

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:44.440
[Guest]: I've also, just because of the things I get involved in, I've had many, many experiences

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:52.360
[Guest]: with people whose need for treatment was acute, immediate, and yet they were not able to access

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:54.960
[Guest]: it for a variety of reasons.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:09:00.840
[Guest]: You know, young women getting thrown out of hospitals at midnight and multiple members

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:04.640
[Guest]: of families dying while waiting for care.

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:12.920
[Guest]: These are terrible things to go through, even for someone who's not immediately impacted.

00:09:12.920 --> 00:09:18.760
[Guest]: And I imagine that these are really bad for the families that are experienced with them.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:26.400
[Guest]: What it tells us is that there is a tremendous price that we are paying for two things.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:33.240
[Guest]: Weak governance, not just in India, but around the world, and a really sharp disconnect between

00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:38.120
[Guest]: the things that ought to matter and the things that seem to matter in political life.

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:43.280
[Guest]: Around the world, frankly, you would think this is the kind of problem that ought not

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:44.280
[Guest]: to exist.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:46.960
[Guest]: It's a bit like climate change, right?

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:53.480
[Guest]: You think that a bunch of sensible people with sufficient decency and foresight ought

00:09:53.480 --> 00:09:58.200
[Guest]: to be able to anticipate and solve a problem like that.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:05.200
[Guest]: But this whole sensible people with sufficient decency and foresight, it seems like a quest

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:08.600
[Guest]: for another planet or something like that.

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:17.360
[Guest]: In a way, it's becoming harshly clear to a lot of people that somewhere along the narrative

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:24.120
[Guest]: of even democracy that we have built for ourselves, there are very large gaps, and those gaps

00:10:24.120 --> 00:10:27.920
[Guest]: become apparent at times like this.

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:32.440
[Guest]: And there is an important response that is needed to say, how are we going to bridge

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:33.440
[Guest]: those gaps?

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:41.000
[Guest]: How do we make sure that people in positions of authority are also responsible and actually

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.760
[Guest]: proactively do the things that we'd like them to do?

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:52.360
[Guest]: I think this pandemic really should provoke a lot more of us to asking those questions.

00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:58.000
[Guest]: Some of us have been fortunate not to have suffered terrible consequences as a result

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.920
[Guest]: of it, but it's now reached a stage where each of us knows at least several other people

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:05.920
[Guest]: who have suffered greatly.

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:13.480
[Guest]: And really, that has been the difficult part of the pandemic, just knowing what else is

00:11:13.480 --> 00:11:20.000
[Guest]: going on and also a sense of helplessness about the whole thing.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.560
[Guest]: I can imagine that if people like me who are reasonably well-connected with governance

00:11:24.560 --> 00:11:32.240
[Guest]: systems feel this way, that for a lot of other people, just shutting it out of their minds

00:11:32.240 --> 00:11:34.760
[Guest]: entirely seems the only option.

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:41.520
[Guest]: And maybe that's what explains so much of the non-compliance with good practices that

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:47.960
[Guest]: people don't even want to think about at this point, because it's scary, it's not clear

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:50.360
[Guest]: what they should do.

00:11:50.360 --> 00:11:51.360
[Guest]: It's bizarre.

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:56.240
[Guest]: The number of circumstances in which you have to do the right thing is so large that at

00:11:56.240 --> 00:12:02.680
[Guest]: some point, people will just throw up their hands and say, hell, if it happens, it happens.

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:03.680
[Guest]: It is scary.

00:12:03.680 --> 00:12:08.040
[Guest]: I'm hoping it's not going to be more than, initially I thought it was going to be a three,

00:12:08.040 --> 00:12:13.960
[Guest]: six, nine month thing, but now it seems every day like it's going to be another three, six

00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:17.680
[Guest]: or nine months rather than just three, six or nine months.

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:26.040
[Guest]: I think we should prepare for coming out of this in a reasonable way only by the summer

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:27.920
[Guest]: of next year.

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:33.120
[Guest]: The winter could be a difficult time globally.

00:12:33.120 --> 00:12:34.120
[Guest]: What else can you do?

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:38.520
[Guest]: And there are certain parts of the economy, certain types of livelihoods that have been

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:41.200
[Guest]: massively impacted.

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:46.160
[Guest]: And in India in particular, because we don't have the public systems to support people

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:51.280
[Guest]: through these kinds of downturns, a lot of people are vulnerable as a result.

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:58.640
[Guest]: And I imagine that at least 50 million people have gone into poverty as a result of the

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:03.720
[Guest]: pandemic who previously would not have been thought of as poor people.

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:12.280
[Guest]: And it has set back our development journey by at least six to 10 years in pure numerical

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:13.280
[Guest]: terms.

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:17.440
[Guest]: A lot of that is true around the world.

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:22.880
[Guest]: Like I said, at this point, you're reduced to living through it and finding your way

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:24.880
[Guest]: back each day at a time.

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:25.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:30.880
[Amit Varma]: The economist, Abhisachi Kaur, I think he posted this graph on Twitter where he showed,

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:34.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, given certain assumptions about how much we will grow, how much, you know,

00:13:34.920 --> 00:13:36.160
[Amit Varma]: COVID has set us back.

00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:42.320
[Amit Varma]: And I think his calculation was that it will take till 2033 until our economy goes to where

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:46.600
[Amit Varma]: it would otherwise have been in a time of normal growth at five and a half.

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:49.320
[Amit Varma]: And he was calculating at COVID plus seven, something like that.

00:13:49.320 --> 00:13:54.640
[Amit Varma]: I was also kind of struck by what you said about people shutting it out because they

00:13:54.640 --> 00:13:56.240
[Amit Varma]: simply can't understand what's going on.

00:13:56.240 --> 00:14:00.400
[Amit Varma]: So you shut it out and you're in denial and that leads you to behave in odd ways.

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:04.180
[Amit Varma]: Because it strikes me that that is what we do in a sense in life itself.

00:14:04.180 --> 00:14:10.120
[Amit Varma]: That most people, you know, the very truth of our mortality, for example, or the complexity

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:15.920
[Amit Varma]: of the universe, which we can't possibly fathom is so scary that, you know, apart from doing

00:14:15.920 --> 00:14:20.880
[Amit Varma]: things like inventing religions to build narratives to come to terms with it, we also sort of

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:21.880
[Amit Varma]: shut it out.

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:26.200
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that this is kind of, in a sense, a more localized version of that,

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:28.140
[Amit Varma]: that certain things are not in your control.

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:29.140
[Amit Varma]: So what do you do?

00:14:29.140 --> 00:14:30.400
[Amit Varma]: You go in denial about it.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:35.400
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to sort of take a little Chinese box approach to the rest of the episode in

00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:39.080
[Amit Varma]: the sense that the core of the episode and what I would really like to talk about, obviously,

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:44.880
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, urban governance and your ideas on how cities and urban governance should

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:46.920
[Amit Varma]: be reformed and all of that.

00:14:46.920 --> 00:14:51.440
[Amit Varma]: Before I get to that, I also want to talk a bit about map unity and lithium and, you

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:53.620
[Amit Varma]: know, briefly discuss that.

00:14:53.620 --> 00:14:58.120
[Amit Varma]: But before even that, I kind of want to come back to the earlier question of what you do

00:14:58.120 --> 00:15:01.760
[Amit Varma]: in your downtime, because just, you know, something that I've been thinking about recently

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:07.640
[Amit Varma]: also is that these seemingly inconsequential choices that we often make at a personal level

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:09.400
[Amit Varma]: of how will I spend my time?

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:10.400
[Amit Varma]: Will I read a book?

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:12.640
[Amit Varma]: Will I, you know, play a game on my mobile?

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:16.360
[Amit Varma]: Will I check Twitter obsessively to see who's trolling me now?

00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:20.600
[Amit Varma]: Will I watch something on Netflix or will I listen to a podcast and go running?

00:15:20.600 --> 00:15:25.040
[Amit Varma]: All of these choices are actually far more consequential than we imagine, because over

00:15:25.040 --> 00:15:29.360
[Amit Varma]: a period of time, they sort of shape our thinking and they shape who we are.

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:33.640
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, these seemingly trivial choices make all the difference.

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:39.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm curious about one, do you think consciously about, you know, your productivity, for example,

00:15:39.920 --> 00:15:42.460
[Amit Varma]: and how you spend your day and how you divide your time?

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:44.560
[Amit Varma]: And also, what do you do in your downtime to relax?

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:45.920
[Amit Varma]: And what are your guilty pleasures?

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:50.320
[Amit Varma]: Do you spend three hours every day surfing music videos on YouTube, as some of us do?

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:53.640
[Amit Varma]: What's, you know, tell me, give me a sense of what that is like.

00:15:53.640 --> 00:16:01.200
[Guest]: Well, you remember from our earlier conversation, my 15 minutes to 20 minutes every day of trying

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:06.080
[Guest]: to do a few things that keep a certain rhythm to my life.

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:07.720
[Guest]: I still try to do that.

00:16:07.720 --> 00:16:14.120
[Guest]: And I don't think that gets affected very much by a pandemic, even.

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:18.400
[Guest]: It's kind of odd to say that even a pandemic doesn't affect something.

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:23.960
[Guest]: But since it's only 15-20 minutes a day, I'm able to do that, definitely.

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:27.680
[Guest]: One of the things that has come down is the ability to meet strangers, and I'm trying

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:32.880
[Guest]: to be more deliberate about that, especially online.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:40.960
[Guest]: But broadly, what I find is that in some way, not needing to travel as much has actually

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:47.880
[Guest]: opened up time to do things that otherwise go in simply commuting or travel.

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:52.600
[Guest]: And some things have happened, I think, because I have the additional time.

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:57.160
[Guest]: I've been able to think more carefully about education, for example, and it's an interesting

00:16:57.160 --> 00:17:01.640
[Guest]: time to think about education because the whole education framework has now collapsed

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:04.840
[Guest]: as a result of the pandemic.

00:17:04.840 --> 00:17:11.520
[Guest]: And all our assumptions about the delivery and the governance of education, especially

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:15.840
[Guest]: public education, have entirely gone for a toss.

00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:21.600
[Guest]: And if we are smart about this, we will take the opportunity to reimagine education.

00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:25.560
[Guest]: But even without that, there's an increasing set of choices that people are starting to

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:33.200
[Guest]: make for their own learning, which I think will radically alter the landscape of learning.

00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:37.080
[Guest]: And that's something that I've been able to spend more time thinking about because of

00:17:37.080 --> 00:17:39.960
[Guest]: the pandemic.

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:43.520
[Guest]: I shut down the office because of the pandemic.

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:48.800
[Guest]: It didn't seem like it was worth paying rent to keep up an establishment.

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:55.640
[Guest]: I instead rented the neighboring flat, which is actually a much more useful way to spend

00:17:55.640 --> 00:18:01.720
[Guest]: the same amount of money because it gives you close by additional space to work out

00:18:01.720 --> 00:18:04.840
[Guest]: of and also have as a personal space.

00:18:04.840 --> 00:18:08.880
[Guest]: So people at home are not complaining that you're always on the phone or always on the

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:13.440
[Guest]: computer and there are enough spaces to do that quietly.

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:19.040
[Guest]: So I'm sort of able to have even this conversation with you for more than a couple of hours without

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:23.520
[Guest]: worrying that anyone's going to get annoyed about that.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:31.640
[Guest]: So things like that, I think of certain adjustments that people make, educate each of us about

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:36.600
[Unknown]: what the alternatives could be, the things that we've previously taken for granted.

00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:42.360
[Guest]: You have to go to an office, you have to work certain times of the day, work in certain

00:18:42.360 --> 00:18:44.960
[Guest]: ways, you have to have face-to-face meetings.

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:50.480
[Guest]: All of these things are under tremendous reassessment and scrutiny now.

00:18:50.480 --> 00:18:55.600
[Guest]: And it seems like at least 60% of what we did previously was probably not as useful

00:18:55.600 --> 00:18:58.080
[Guest]: as we thought it was.

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:01.840
[Guest]: And so you could imagine it being different.

00:19:01.840 --> 00:19:07.040
[Guest]: I've always been in favor of a six and a half to seven hour workday.

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:12.000
[Guest]: And I generally don't think that people can be productive beyond that anyway.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:15.760
[Guest]: Even school days, I think shouldn't be more than four and a half to five hours.

00:19:15.760 --> 00:19:21.120
[Guest]: I can't imagine that you can send kids to six and seven hours of school and think that

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:25.040
[Guest]: you're adding to their learning beyond the first three or four hours.

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:32.160
[Guest]: So I think this reconstruction of time for various purposes is really the big thing that

00:19:32.160 --> 00:19:34.160
[Guest]: I've been toying with during the pandemic.

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:40.240
[Guest]: Of late, I've started going out a little bit more and meeting more people and feeling comfortable

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:41.240
[Guest]: about that.

00:19:41.240 --> 00:19:47.480
[Guest]: I also know that in doing that, all of us are taking risks, both for ourselves and unfortunately

00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:48.480
[Guest]: for others too.

00:19:48.480 --> 00:19:53.960
[Guest]: There's no way to come out of this without that risk.

00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:58.960
[Guest]: And some of it is, you can tell yourself it's a calculated risk, but if you don't know the

00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:03.520
[Guest]: formula, it's difficult to tell what a calculation will lead you to.

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:10.160
[Guest]: I feel like we're taking calculated risks without knowing the equation itself, but it

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:11.160
[Guest]: is what it is.

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:16.720
[Guest]: I've been reading huge stacks of books that have piled up over the years where I would

00:20:16.720 --> 00:20:21.520
[Guest]: – and normally when I buy a book, I write down the date on which I buy the book and

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:24.800
[Guest]: try to see when I actually get around to reading it.

00:20:24.800 --> 00:20:30.600
[Guest]: And if those gaps are more than 18 months or 24 months, I slow down the book buying

00:20:30.600 --> 00:20:35.200
[Guest]: telling myself that I'd better read the ones that I've already bought.

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:41.880
[Guest]: I think now I've brought it down to six months or seven months of gap, which presumably that's

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:43.520
[Unknown]: because I've been able to read a lot more.

00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:48.360
[Guest]: And I have some neighbors who seem to read five times as fast as I do, probably as fast

00:20:48.360 --> 00:20:49.360
[Guest]: as you do.

00:20:49.360 --> 00:20:56.080
[Guest]: And so that motivates me to talk to them about what they're reading and read some of those

00:20:56.080 --> 00:20:57.080
[Guest]: things as well.

00:20:57.080 --> 00:21:00.920
[Guest]: I've been watching a lot of the TED Talks.

00:21:00.920 --> 00:21:06.280
[Guest]: For no particular reason, I just kind of randomly pick one and watch that.

00:21:06.280 --> 00:21:11.880
[Guest]: It's amazing what a variety of topics get covered in TED.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:18.560
[Guest]: Many, many years ago, when I first got introduced to CRISP by one of my friends, it seemed like

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:24.440
[Guest]: it was really a platform for ideas, and each of those ideas was a very powerful thing.

00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:26.320
[Guest]: I think today it's become even more than that.

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:28.520
[Guest]: It's not just a platform for ideas.

00:21:28.520 --> 00:21:35.560
[Guest]: It's even a platform for stances that people take towards many things.

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:40.400
[Guest]: And therefore, it sort of lets you think powerfully about each of those as well.

00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:45.920
[Guest]: You may agree, you may not agree, but I think it's useful to have a forum like that, where

00:21:45.920 --> 00:21:53.760
[Guest]: you can sort of see things that are stated provocatively and succinctly and ask yourself,

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:57.160
[Guest]: what do I think about that?

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:05.480
[Guest]: And also, I'm thinking more about Bill Drayton's idea of cognitive empathy, where he says...

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:10.400
[Guest]: Bill Drayton started the Ashoka Fellowship, the Social Entrepreneurship Fellowship around

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:18.560
[Guest]: the world, and he talks about this idea of not just caring about others, but actively

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:25.760
[Guest]: doing something that allows you to feel that your empathy is cognitive as well, rather

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:30.120
[Guest]: than merely an acknowledgement of other people's difficulties.

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:34.880
[Guest]: And so, you can take problem after problem and ask yourself, what's the difference between

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:37.800
[Guest]: mere empathy and cognitive empathy?

00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:43.320
[Guest]: And how I can be closer to the second one than to the first one?

00:22:43.320 --> 00:22:46.200
[Guest]: And God knows there are enough problems to work on.

00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:53.000
[Guest]: So you can say, if I care about public education, what are three things that I ought to be doing

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.480
[Unknown]: to convince myself that I actually care about this?

00:22:57.480 --> 00:22:58.480
[Unknown]: I think a lot of people...

00:22:58.480 --> 00:22:59.480
[Unknown]: We're seeing this.

00:22:59.480 --> 00:23:05.080
[Guest]: A lot of people care about a lot of things, but if you probe the extent to which they're

00:23:05.080 --> 00:23:10.160
[Guest]: acting on what they care about, it doesn't often reflect the extent to which they say

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:11.160
[Guest]: they care about it.

00:23:11.160 --> 00:23:15.600
[Guest]: I don't think that makes them hypocritical.

00:23:15.600 --> 00:23:21.400
[Guest]: I think it just means that there is still one more step that they need to take.

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:25.840
[Guest]: And I've sort of been learning about such deliberate steps and how to take them.

00:23:25.840 --> 00:23:31.040
[Guest]: So a lot of the day gets filled up in simply saying, how many deliberate steps can I take

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:36.600
[Guest]: that I actually don't need to take to continue with my life, but which I think are important

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:40.440
[Guest]: to take, interesting to take, things like that.

00:23:40.440 --> 00:23:41.440
[Guest]: And there are certain things you can't do.

00:23:41.440 --> 00:23:42.440
[Guest]: You can't go swimming.

00:23:42.440 --> 00:23:46.720
[Guest]: You can't go whatever, five other things that you would otherwise have done.

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:50.040
[Guest]: So that frees up time for stuff like that.

00:23:50.040 --> 00:23:55.040
[Guest]: I thought about getting an exercise machine at home and then decided that that was probably

00:23:55.040 --> 00:23:56.040
[Guest]: overkill.

00:23:56.040 --> 00:24:03.240
[Guest]: And I somehow don't see myself doing that very often, even if I were to get that machine.

00:24:03.240 --> 00:24:08.480
[Guest]: But be that as it may, I think we've come to a very different imagination of time because

00:24:08.480 --> 00:24:15.200
[Guest]: almost a year is now going to go by in our lives as a result of the pandemic in ways

00:24:15.200 --> 00:24:17.120
[Guest]: that we did not anticipate at all.

00:24:17.120 --> 00:24:19.320
[Guest]: And a year is a very long time.

00:24:19.320 --> 00:24:23.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm glad you're not getting an exercise machine, because if I could turn my laptop camera right

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:27.360
[Amit Varma]: now, I could show you an elliptical in the corner and, you know, there's jeans hanging

00:24:27.360 --> 00:24:30.560
[Amit Varma]: from the handle and there's a pair of old shoes on the stepper.

00:24:30.560 --> 00:24:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And that's clearly, you know, not something that's worked for me, at least.

00:24:35.440 --> 00:24:39.800
[Amit Varma]: I was, you know, also struck by how you spoke about, you know, reduce work hours and we

00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:41.120
[Amit Varma]: don't really need so many hours.

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:45.760
[Amit Varma]: And I just came across this quote today morning, this tweet, in fact, by Naval Ravikant, where

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:49.960
[Amit Varma]: he says, and I'll read it out quote, you don't have eight creative problem solving hours

00:24:49.960 --> 00:24:50.960
[Amit Varma]: in the day.

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:54.720
[Amit Varma]: You have to spend your time wisely, a strop quote.

00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:58.960
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of strikes me because more and more as I try to get more done with my time,

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:03.600
[Amit Varma]: I realized that my best hours are when I wake up and I'm fresh in the morning and I absolutely

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:06.240
[Amit Varma]: have to maximize that and all of those things.

00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And the reason this quote was even handy for me, and I thought I'd ask you about this,

00:25:09.600 --> 00:25:14.520
[Amit Varma]: because this again came to mind when you spoke about watching TED Talks, is one of the things

00:25:14.520 --> 00:25:18.160
[Amit Varma]: I've been, again, thinking about recently is that, look, I might read a lot of books

00:25:18.160 --> 00:25:22.320
[Amit Varma]: and I might watch a lot of videos and I might get in different amounts of knowledge and

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:25.080
[Amit Varma]: insight from elsewhere, but how do I retain it?

00:25:25.080 --> 00:25:29.920
[Amit Varma]: And especially as I go deeper into middle age, my memory is just horrible and I'll just

00:25:29.920 --> 00:25:31.160
[Amit Varma]: forget a lot of stuff.

00:25:31.160 --> 00:25:36.360
[Amit Varma]: And I am very struck, therefore, by this concept of the second brain, which, you know, I think

00:25:36.360 --> 00:25:41.840
[Amit Varma]: pioneered by someone called Tiago Forte, where the idea is that you use tools and you use

00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:47.440
[Amit Varma]: apps, so all the knowledge that you're gathering, you kind of collate them in, you know, what

00:25:47.440 --> 00:25:52.320
[Amit Varma]: he describes as a second brain, which is a collection of apps and tools which helps you

00:25:52.320 --> 00:25:53.320
[Amit Varma]: keep all of this together.

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:57.080
[Amit Varma]: So in fact, what I've recently been doing a lot is using this incredible app called

00:25:57.080 --> 00:26:01.680
[Amit Varma]: Rome Research, where anytime I watch a TED Talk, for example, which I like, I'll actually

00:26:01.680 --> 00:26:03.160
[Amit Varma]: take notes from it.

00:26:03.160 --> 00:26:05.880
[Amit Varma]: And it has nesting, it has bidirectional linking.

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:07.200
[Amit Varma]: So it is always there.

00:26:07.200 --> 00:26:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Earlier, when I took notes on books, for example, for my research or whatever, there would be

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:15.040
[Amit Varma]: disconnected word documents and so on and so forth.

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:19.720
[Amit Varma]: But here, you know, I've got a master doc, which says, Ashwin Mahesh, and I might have

00:26:19.720 --> 00:26:22.600
[Amit Varma]: links from the notes from the episode we did together.

00:26:22.600 --> 00:26:27.080
[Amit Varma]: And I might have further notes from the paper you sent me, the presentation you sent me

00:26:27.080 --> 00:26:28.960
[Amit Varma]: before we recorded this episode.

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:30.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's all there forever.

00:26:30.200 --> 00:26:31.800
[Amit Varma]: It's linked back and forth.

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:34.160
[Amit Varma]: And it's quite kind of wonderful.

00:26:34.160 --> 00:26:38.880
[Amit Varma]: Do you have, you know, since your thinking is so systemic and clear, do you also have

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:46.320
[Amit Varma]: ways of sort of making sure that you sort of retain your knowledge and insights from

00:26:46.320 --> 00:26:48.440
[Amit Varma]: all the reading that you do and the watching that you do?

00:26:48.440 --> 00:26:55.520
[Guest]: Well, I wish I could say yes, but you know, the answer is probably closer to no than yes.

00:26:55.520 --> 00:27:00.280
[Guest]: What I had tried to do off late, though, is try to change that.

00:27:00.280 --> 00:27:07.080
[Guest]: And I sort of forced myself into accepting certain things as useful instruments for that

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:08.080
[Guest]: change.

00:27:08.080 --> 00:27:14.240
[Guest]: And I've decided that teaching what I know is a useful instrument for such change.

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:18.760
[Guest]: Because in order to teach, I first have to write down what it is that I know.

00:27:18.760 --> 00:27:26.200
[Guest]: And that sort of gets me into some part of the documentation, organization of what I

00:27:26.200 --> 00:27:31.120
[Guest]: know, so that I can then subsequently tell it to a few more people.

00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:37.360
[Unknown]: There are schools of public policy, schools of problem solving, you know, professors interested

00:27:37.360 --> 00:27:40.520
[Guest]: in problem solving courses.

00:27:40.520 --> 00:27:46.840
[Guest]: So I've started collaborating with a few of them, and in 2021, in particular, I plan to

00:27:46.840 --> 00:27:51.960
[Guest]: teach at least in three different such environments.

00:27:51.960 --> 00:27:54.880
[Guest]: And hopefully, the act of doing that helps.

00:27:54.880 --> 00:28:02.680
[Guest]: Also, I've sort of tried to document some things on my website, just because of the

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:07.040
[Guest]: diversity of things I get into, sort of just as a way of organizing my thoughts.

00:28:07.040 --> 00:28:12.880
[Guest]: And also, as a way of repeatedly asking, what are the ideas that inform the actions?

00:28:12.880 --> 00:28:17.840
[Guest]: Because you can get into a lot of actions without asking yourself what ideas inform

00:28:17.840 --> 00:28:23.200
[Unknown]: your actions, or what ideas you're coming to as a result of your actions, or even what

00:28:23.200 --> 00:28:27.080
[Guest]: ideas you appear to be endorsing as a result of your actions.

00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:33.880
[Guest]: So I actually sort of have spent some time putting that material together on the website.

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:41.640
[Guest]: And yeah, I think some discipline in documentation will arise as a result of all this in the

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:44.080
[Guest]: next six months, at least.

00:28:44.080 --> 00:28:46.640
[Guest]: It remains to be seen whether I can sustain that.

00:28:46.640 --> 00:28:49.320
[Guest]: Sometimes you put the first material together.

00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:54.120
[Guest]: I taught a course at IAM many years ago called Reinventing Government.

00:28:54.120 --> 00:28:59.000
[Guest]: After three years, I decided that the course material itself needed reinventing.

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:05.240
[Guest]: So in a way, you can take good first steps in any direction.

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:09.920
[Guest]: But really, it is quite important to keep taking those second steps and third steps,

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:11.720
[Guest]: which make the first step meaningful.

00:29:11.720 --> 00:29:18.280
[Guest]: Otherwise, you can sort of take lots of journeys of first steps and never get anywhere.

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:21.880
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned that you were also sort of thinking about education deeply because

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:22.880
[Amit Varma]: of the pandemic.

00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:26.920
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, you know, we can see the surface reasons and the first order reasons

00:29:26.920 --> 00:29:31.720
[Amit Varma]: for thinking about education, because obviously, instead of going to a school physically, kids

00:29:31.720 --> 00:29:34.080
[Amit Varma]: are, you know, getting educated on Zoom.

00:29:34.080 --> 00:29:38.280
[Amit Varma]: But I have, and again, I'd like to know your thoughts on this, because, you know, it struck

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:44.880
[Amit Varma]: me for a while that our education system is incredibly outdated in every possible way,

00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:49.160
[Amit Varma]: not just the obvious ones, that we are stuck with the inertia of the past, that in a sense,

00:29:49.160 --> 00:29:53.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, economists call about isomorphic mimicry, which is you take a policy from another

00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:57.060
[Amit Varma]: place, and you try to implement it wherever you are.

00:29:57.060 --> 00:30:01.240
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that there is also a version of that happening across time, where something

00:30:01.240 --> 00:30:07.580
[Amit Varma]: that worked at one time or that made intuitive sense is completely unsuited to another time.

00:30:07.580 --> 00:30:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And we simply we just assume that our kids will go to school for 10 years or 12 years

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:16.360
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, they will be college, these will be the subjects, these will be the social

00:30:16.360 --> 00:30:21.720
[Amit Varma]: sciences in their different silos, these will be the whatever and you know, one of the consequences

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:27.440
[Amit Varma]: of that not working that being dysfunctional, in a sense, is that part of our jobs prices

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:32.480
[Amit Varma]: is that one, of course, there aren't enough jobs, but also that a lot of the people who

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:38.380
[Amit Varma]: are getting degrees, including higher education degrees, have no skills, they are in equipped

00:30:38.380 --> 00:30:40.680
[Amit Varma]: for anything in the real world.

00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:45.960
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that at some level, the pandemic might be an opportunity to really

00:30:45.960 --> 00:30:51.800
[Amit Varma]: sit down and cast away the inertia of the past and think anew about, you know, everything

00:30:51.800 --> 00:30:53.200
[Amit Varma]: from the bottom up.

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:55.200
[Amit Varma]: What are your sort of thoughts on this?

00:30:55.200 --> 00:30:57.120
[Amit Varma]: Because you mentioned you've been thinking a lot about this.

00:30:57.120 --> 00:30:58.120
[Amit Varma]: So you know?

00:30:58.120 --> 00:30:59.120
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:30:59.120 --> 00:31:07.400
[Guest]: So the conclusion, or at least one conclusion I've come to, is that we have failed to ask

00:31:07.400 --> 00:31:16.000
[Guest]: and answer an important question, and that question is, who should teach?

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.760
[Guest]: It's an interesting question, if you think about it, who should teach?

00:31:18.760 --> 00:31:24.280
[Guest]: We'll come to all the other things later, where they should teach, how they should teach,

00:31:24.280 --> 00:31:28.000
[Guest]: and all of that, but who should teach?

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:32.880
[Guest]: It seems logical to say that people who know things should teach, if you don't have anything

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:34.400
[Guest]: to teach.

00:31:34.400 --> 00:31:42.240
[Guest]: So and therefore, what the pandemic has essentially created is a situation where merely knowing

00:31:42.240 --> 00:31:45.760
[Guest]: things is enough to be allowed to teach.

00:31:45.760 --> 00:31:51.280
[Guest]: And of course, to some extent, even before the pandemic, MOOCs and Coursera and 20 other

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:56.360
[Guest]: things had begun to make that possible.

00:31:56.360 --> 00:32:03.880
[Guest]: Essentially saying to the formal system that the way in which you decide who should teach

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:10.120
[Guest]: is unacceptable to me, because what the formal systems have done is they have connected too

00:32:10.120 --> 00:32:14.240
[Guest]: many other questions to this question.

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:20.960
[Guest]: So if Amit should teach, because he knows, let's say, podcasting.

00:32:20.960 --> 00:32:26.320
[Guest]: So if Amit should teach podcasting, where should he teach podcasting?

00:32:26.320 --> 00:32:32.320
[Guest]: If he taught it online in a loosely certified way, that's one thing, but for you to teach

00:32:32.320 --> 00:32:39.520
[Guest]: podcasting in a quote-unquote recognized institution is much, much harder when you think about

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:40.520
[Guest]: it.

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:47.920
[Guest]: You might be the king of podcasting, and you're pretty close to it, but the thing is that

00:32:47.920 --> 00:32:54.960
[Guest]: you wouldn't be allowed to teach this in a formal setting as it stands now, because the

00:32:54.960 --> 00:32:58.200
[Guest]: setting doesn't permit that anymore.

00:32:58.200 --> 00:33:03.880
[Guest]: The second thing is that you could turn the question on its head and say, who should you

00:33:03.880 --> 00:33:04.880
[Guest]: teach?

00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:07.920
[Guest]: So who should you teach?

00:33:07.920 --> 00:33:13.240
[Guest]: So let's say that Amit is 16 years old and he wants to be a cricket player, and what

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:14.240
[Guest]: should you teach him?

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:20.360
[Guest]: Chemistry and mathematics and history or a lot of cricket, and maybe cricket statistics

00:33:20.360 --> 00:33:26.240
[Guest]: and cricket broadcasting and cricket commentary and cricket sports medicine and things like

00:33:26.240 --> 00:33:27.240
[Guest]: that.

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:35.160
[Guest]: Actually, I think we've gone from the important question to the unimportant ones really quickly,

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:40.440
[Guest]: and the unimportant ones are easier for governments to get a grip on, and that's really why they've

00:33:40.440 --> 00:33:41.440
[Guest]: gone to the unimportant ones.

00:33:41.440 --> 00:33:44.440
[Guest]: Historically, in fact, if you thought about it, people who knew things taught.

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:52.040
[Guest]: That's all it was, there wasn't any blessing for that beyond the fact that they knew things.

00:33:52.040 --> 00:33:58.440
[Guest]: But with mass education in particular, has come the expectation that there should be

00:33:58.440 --> 00:34:01.540
[Guest]: controls and filters on who should teach.

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:08.040
[Guest]: So certification has become a big part of the teaching, being allowed to teach.

00:34:08.040 --> 00:34:13.440
[Guest]: But certification, I mean, I remember a friend of mine that I am telling me that in India,

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:18.680
[Guest]: we probably have the world's largest gap between certification and learning.

00:34:18.680 --> 00:34:22.640
[Guest]: Just because someone has a certificate doesn't mean that they actually know anything.

00:34:22.640 --> 00:34:27.200
[Guest]: You've seen news reports about students taking exams in Bihar, where they're climbing in

00:34:27.200 --> 00:34:29.600
[Guest]: and out of windows to be able to copy from each other.

00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:36.440
[Guest]: And you're thinking, surely this isn't anything that any employer will find credible.

00:34:36.440 --> 00:34:42.680
[Guest]: And so I think what the pandemic has done is it has basically turned the system on its

00:34:42.680 --> 00:34:49.920
[Guest]: head and said, no one really took you seriously anyway, now they don't even have to take you

00:34:49.920 --> 00:34:50.920
[Guest]: seriously.

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:57.840
[Guest]: But there are people who still say this is just for the elite, maybe 10% of the population

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:03.040
[Guest]: can make choices like this, 90% of the population can't make choices that are any different

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:08.520
[Guest]: from the conventional ones available from the 1500s or the 1600s.

00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:15.400
[Guest]: That's probably still true, but new things, when you look at even MOOCs and online education,

00:35:15.400 --> 00:35:19.400
[Unknown]: they weren't very big 10, 15 years ago.

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:25.160
[Unknown]: But two years ago, I read somewhere that 20% of all degrees being given online, the MOOCs

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:30.200
[Guest]: were giving out at least that many certificates as 20% of all physical degrees.

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:36.360
[Guest]: So in a way, the numbers are growing, the modularity of learning is expanding.

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:43.000
[Guest]: That's an important thing, that this tight correlation between your age and the intensity

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:44.360
[Guest]: of your learning.

00:35:44.360 --> 00:35:51.400
[Guest]: So if you were to try to learn basic English at age 11, people would find that odd and

00:35:51.400 --> 00:35:54.360
[Guest]: ask why haven't you learned it earlier?

00:35:54.360 --> 00:36:00.640
[Guest]: Or even if you were basic Hindi or basic Kannada, whatever, whatever be your medium of instruction,

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:02.280
[Guest]: people would find it odd that you haven't learned it.

00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:07.640
[Guest]: But if you were to learn basic Russian at age 11 in India, nobody would think that there's

00:36:07.640 --> 00:36:08.640
[Unknown]: anything wrong.

00:36:08.640 --> 00:36:11.800
[Guest]: In fact, you could learn basic Russian at age 61, and nobody would think that there's

00:36:11.800 --> 00:36:12.800
[Guest]: anything wrong with that.

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:18.240
[Guest]: I actually think there's nothing wrong with learning basic physics when you're 61 too,

00:36:18.240 --> 00:36:22.000
[Guest]: or learning basic mathematics when you're 61 too.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:27.320
[Guest]: But we have a system of learning that has tightly coupled age to learning.

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:33.880
[Guest]: And not only that, it has sort of bracketed those ages, all 15-year-olds are in whatever,

00:36:33.880 --> 00:36:39.920
[Guest]: 10th grade, all 13-year-olds are in 8th grade, so on and so forth, which is a bizarre thing

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:42.360
[Guest]: in some way.

00:36:42.360 --> 00:36:51.640
[Guest]: Education is too important and too personal to the learner to expect that any form of

00:36:51.640 --> 00:36:56.200
[Guest]: it can result in learning through conformity.

00:36:56.200 --> 00:37:03.000
[Guest]: The system demands that we abandon conformity, but conformity is the thing that the state

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:10.360
[Guest]: likes, the state is comfortable with, and that is the tension that needs to be sorted

00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:11.360
[Guest]: now.

00:37:11.360 --> 00:37:17.600
[Guest]: I sort of, especially with Ken Robinson passing away this year, I spent a lot of time reading

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:23.320
[Guest]: and watching him, and my sense of it is that we're still not comfortable, and this has

00:37:23.320 --> 00:37:27.680
[Guest]: parallels with governance in general, we're still not comfortable trusting the school

00:37:27.680 --> 00:37:32.440
[Guest]: administrator or the school principal in a public school system.

00:37:32.440 --> 00:37:37.240
[Guest]: We're still thinking that the school administrator and the school principal is just a delivery

00:37:37.240 --> 00:37:42.760
[Guest]: agent of something that is decided at a much higher level, and no educational institution

00:37:42.760 --> 00:37:46.880
[Guest]: can become good through that stance.

00:37:46.880 --> 00:37:51.120
[Guest]: I feel we have to, and it's the same thing that we see with decentralization of other

00:37:51.120 --> 00:37:58.840
[Guest]: things too, that fundamentally people in a locality are not empowered to be part of decision

00:37:58.840 --> 00:37:59.840
[Guest]: making in that locality.

00:37:59.840 --> 00:38:08.520
[Guest]: There is no force on earth that can fundamentally help produce good outcomes despite that, and

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:13.120
[Guest]: we keep thinking that state governments and national governments are going to solve hyperlocal

00:38:13.120 --> 00:38:14.120
[Guest]: problems.

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:15.960
[Guest]: They're not going to solve hyperlocal problems.

00:38:15.960 --> 00:38:21.080
[Guest]: They have even no visibility into those problems, they have no capacity to respond to those

00:38:21.080 --> 00:38:22.080
[Guest]: problems.

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:25.080
[Guest]: A lot of people think that in India the national government is going to solve a lot of problems.

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:29.320
[Unknown]: The national government doesn't even have the staff to solve 90% of the problems that

00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:31.800
[Guest]: people care about.

00:38:31.800 --> 00:38:35.360
[Guest]: Even the few schemes that they run are actually implemented by state governments.

00:38:35.360 --> 00:38:41.880
[Guest]: So in a way, I don't think that we have any capacity for problem solving in administration,

00:38:41.880 --> 00:38:47.560
[Guest]: in public administration, that can be separated from decentralization, and that is really

00:38:47.560 --> 00:38:57.160
[Guest]: the problem, that there is a tension between the growing numbers of people moving to cities

00:38:57.160 --> 00:39:04.360
[Guest]: and the large agglomerations that produces, and the reality that despite such agglomeration,

00:39:04.360 --> 00:39:09.320
[Guest]: it is decentralized participatory problem solving that is actually going to make even

00:39:09.320 --> 00:39:12.520
[Guest]: those agglomerations work well.

00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:17.920
[Guest]: And I find that that is repeatedly true in many, many disciplines.

00:39:17.920 --> 00:39:23.960
[Guest]: Education is available in a very different way, but it still needs to be personal and

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:27.000
[Guest]: child-centered in some way.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:33.720
[Guest]: Skilling is thought of only as sort of an afterthought, that if you fail in formal education,

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:39.320
[Guest]: then you go to a vocational program, which is very silly because 90% of the jobs out

00:39:39.320 --> 00:39:43.880
[Guest]: there are not jobs you would get through formal education anyway.

00:39:43.880 --> 00:39:48.880
[Guest]: If anything, vocational learning should be the norm, and only those who need more than

00:39:48.880 --> 00:39:55.360
[Guest]: that should be going to formal learning, but we have the opposite system in many cases.

00:39:55.360 --> 00:40:05.360
[Guest]: So what I've been reflecting on is how comfortable we have become with the status quo, and why

00:40:05.360 --> 00:40:09.440
[Guest]: systems of administration struggle to overcome the status quo.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:14.160
[Guest]: There's a very interesting experiment that was a professor at Harvard called Lant Pritchett.

00:40:14.160 --> 00:40:15.160
[Guest]: You might know Lant.

00:40:15.160 --> 00:40:18.400
[Unknown]: He worked for a while with the Administrative Reforms Commission, too.

00:40:18.400 --> 00:40:23.960
[Guest]: There was one interesting thing that he taught some of us, saying, look, if there are 25

00:40:23.960 --> 00:40:28.120
[Guest]: things that need to change simultaneously, it's very difficult to figure out which one

00:40:28.120 --> 00:40:30.680
[Guest]: you should touch first.

00:40:30.680 --> 00:40:36.600
[Guest]: And so the first exercise you do is to ask yourself, which of these 25 things has the

00:40:36.600 --> 00:40:40.960
[Guest]: potential to have a domino effect on other things?

00:40:40.960 --> 00:40:45.800
[Guest]: And you rank them in that order, and then decide which ones to touch and which ones

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:46.800
[Unknown]: not to touch.

00:40:46.800 --> 00:40:50.280
[Unknown]: So really, so for a lot of public problems, this is what I've been doing now.

00:40:50.280 --> 00:40:53.680
[Unknown]: So here are 10 things that need to change, and as we talk about urbanization, we'll go

00:40:53.680 --> 00:40:58.280
[Guest]: through 10, 15 things that need to change, but if you could only touch one of them, which

00:40:58.280 --> 00:41:03.440
[Guest]: one would you touch, right, because you can't really touch 15 of them until you get into

00:41:03.440 --> 00:41:04.440
[Guest]: government.

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:08.680
[Guest]: And I've seen even friends of mine who get into government and even become chief ministers

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:14.120
[Guest]: sort of have difficulty in touching 15 things at the same time.

00:41:14.120 --> 00:41:19.840
[Guest]: So it's not only about power and authority and decision-making rights.

00:41:19.840 --> 00:41:26.000
[Guest]: It's about actually being able to carry that out in a system that is weak to begin with.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:27.560
[Unknown]: State capacity is very low.

00:41:27.560 --> 00:41:28.560
[Guest]: We have to accept that.

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:33.560
[Guest]: And in a system where the state capacity is low, you can't really pull off all the things

00:41:33.560 --> 00:41:36.400
[Guest]: that you would like to.

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:43.760
[Guest]: The state is nonetheless not comfortable with a greater balance of power between itself

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:49.040
[Guest]: and market and society, and in fact, actively puts out the narrative that market and society

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:51.080
[Guest]: cannot be trusted.

00:41:51.080 --> 00:41:57.680
[Guest]: So in such a situation, it seems like what you're going to get is enduring underdevelopment.

00:41:57.680 --> 00:42:00.720
[Guest]: I mean, look at this election that's going on in Bihar.

00:42:00.720 --> 00:42:05.120
[Guest]: You have two major formations, each of whom has delivered 15 years of lost in the nation

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:09.960
[Guest]: status to that state, and they are the leading contenders for power.

00:42:09.960 --> 00:42:17.960
[Guest]: It's a very sad thing that somehow we have allowed ourselves to arrive at a situation

00:42:17.960 --> 00:42:21.920
[Guest]: which is deeply hostile to the public interest.

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:27.560
[Guest]: But any step that you would take to correct it, it seems like it can only be effective

00:42:27.560 --> 00:42:33.240
[Guest]: if 10 other steps are also taken at the same time, and people find the enormity of all

00:42:33.240 --> 00:42:39.720
[Guest]: that too much, and they just throw up their hands, which perpetuates the problem further.

00:42:39.720 --> 00:42:43.840
[Unknown]: So this is the cycle that you have to overcome, and this is one of the things that I sort

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:49.120
[Unknown]: of, you know, I'm thinking of this Center for Public Problem Solving, right?

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:52.680
[Unknown]: So what is the Center for Public Problem Solving, and what is the problem that it's trying to

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:53.680
[Guest]: overcome?

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:58.520
[Guest]: It's not actually the employability deficit or the governance deficit or whatever.

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:01.960
[Guest]: The problem is not the sectoral thing.

00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:07.000
[Guest]: The problem is how we have organized problem solving itself, right?

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:14.240
[Guest]: If you look at, let's go into organization with a good segue from here.

00:43:14.240 --> 00:43:20.760
[Guest]: If I were to ask you, how many levels of government are there in the constitution and in the laws?

00:43:20.760 --> 00:43:21.760
[Amit Varma]: What would you say?

00:43:21.760 --> 00:43:25.160
[Amit Varma]: I'll think of, you know, in practical terms, what are the effects that we see, and of course

00:43:25.160 --> 00:43:29.960
[Amit Varma]: we see the central level and the state level, and after the 74th amendment, which of course

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:34.520
[Amit Varma]: we'll discuss in much more detail, maybe, you know, a couple of levels below that, but

00:43:34.520 --> 00:43:36.920
[Guest]: that's as far as my understanding would go.

00:43:36.920 --> 00:43:37.920
[Guest]: Okay.

00:43:37.920 --> 00:43:41.320
[Guest]: So most people will say that central, state, and local, right?

00:43:41.320 --> 00:43:47.360
[Guest]: But there are actually five levels of governance that are in the constitution and in the law.

00:43:47.360 --> 00:43:53.000
[Guest]: There is the metropolitan planning level, especially for the larger cities, which exists

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:55.960
[Guest]: in the law, but not in practice.

00:43:55.960 --> 00:44:00.280
[Unknown]: There is also participatory democracy at the local level, which again exists in the law,

00:44:00.280 --> 00:44:05.840
[Guest]: but is very weak at the local level, and participatory democracy in particular, both the planning

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:12.960
[Guest]: level and the participatory level, people think of these things as good to have.

00:44:12.960 --> 00:44:18.360
[Guest]: They're not just good to have, these are must have, and they are required by law.

00:44:18.360 --> 00:44:21.600
[Guest]: Nobody thinks that the state government is good to have.

00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:24.040
[Guest]: They accept that the state government is a must have.

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:26.120
[Guest]: Nobody thinks that the central government is just good to have.

00:44:26.120 --> 00:44:28.200
[Guest]: They accept that it's a must have.

00:44:28.200 --> 00:44:31.520
[Guest]: But there are other things in the law that we simply tell ourselves, these are good to

00:44:31.520 --> 00:44:35.240
[Guest]: have, but it's all right if we don't have them, or somehow we seem to be able to go

00:44:35.240 --> 00:44:36.840
[Guest]: forward without having them.

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:43.400
[Guest]: If an election was not held to a state assembly on time, that would be quite a decision.

00:44:43.400 --> 00:44:49.800
[Unknown]: But if an election is not held to a local council or a planning body, that seems like

00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:53.280
[Guest]: okay, it'll sort of drift on, it'll be sorted out by the courts.

00:44:53.280 --> 00:44:58.520
[Guest]: We don't have an elected council now here in Bangalore, for example, and while one set

00:44:58.520 --> 00:45:04.080
[Guest]: of people are not happy about that, it isn't creating the kind of uproar that the lack

00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:07.840
[Guest]: of a state government or the lack of a national government would.

00:45:07.840 --> 00:45:12.520
[Guest]: There have even been court decisions that local administration is just administration

00:45:12.520 --> 00:45:18.600
[Guest]: and can't even be considered government, which is, these are real challenges, that how we

00:45:18.600 --> 00:45:26.640
[Guest]: think about the structure of government and how we participate is more or less central

00:45:26.640 --> 00:45:29.360
[Guest]: to what we'll actually get from it.

00:45:29.360 --> 00:45:32.320
[Guest]: That we have a very interesting narrative, for example, we think that India is going

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:35.880
[Guest]: to become a superpower and then everybody's going to get educated.

00:45:35.880 --> 00:45:42.960
[Guest]: So it's almost like we expect to arrive at a development outcome before the people of

00:45:42.960 --> 00:45:50.440
[Guest]: the country become developed, and that's a bizarre notion, but it's quite prevalent that

00:45:50.440 --> 00:45:54.440
[Guest]: a lot of people subscribe to that, or even if they don't say it explicitly, they seem

00:45:54.440 --> 00:45:57.160
[Guest]: to believe that's how it's going to happen.

00:45:57.160 --> 00:46:03.080
[Guest]: So what I think it's worth dwelling on and spending a lot of time thinking about is essentially

00:46:03.080 --> 00:46:07.720
[Guest]: this idea of how have we organized ourselves as a society?

00:46:07.720 --> 00:46:10.960
[Guest]: Why have we organized ourselves in this way?

00:46:10.960 --> 00:46:13.200
[Guest]: Who is it deeply unfair to?

00:46:13.200 --> 00:46:17.400
[Guest]: In what ways is it inefficient and just unproductive?

00:46:17.400 --> 00:46:19.920
[Guest]: And why are we doing this to ourselves?

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:23.000
[Guest]: We're not doing this to other people, we're doing this to ourselves.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:28.320
[Guest]: There's a reason why the street outside your house looks the way it does.

00:46:28.320 --> 00:46:35.240
[Guest]: That reason is not some imaginary or actual war with a foreign country, or being struck

00:46:35.240 --> 00:46:38.560
[Guest]: by an asteroid, or any of those sorts of things.

00:46:38.560 --> 00:46:45.360
[Guest]: It's something we have done to ourselves, and therefore I think it's important to be

00:46:45.360 --> 00:46:51.160
[Guest]: deliberate in first stopping to do those things to ourselves, and then starting to do another

00:46:51.160 --> 00:46:53.680
[Guest]: set of things that can change.

00:46:53.680 --> 00:47:01.600
[Guest]: And I really think that urbanization provides a phenomenal opportunity to examine that and

00:47:01.600 --> 00:47:05.640
[Guest]: to actually act in that sphere of influence.

00:47:05.640 --> 00:47:11.000
[Unknown]: And so this has been the fascination for me, that frankly, I got into urbanization as an

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:12.000
[Guest]: ignoramus.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:17.160
[Guest]: I was a climate scientist, I didn't know anything about the city except that I lived in it.

00:47:17.160 --> 00:47:21.480
[Unknown]: And I've always lived in a big city by a lot, other than nine months when I lived in a small

00:47:21.480 --> 00:47:22.480
[Guest]: town in Virginia.

00:47:22.480 --> 00:47:28.320
[Guest]: I've always lived in a big city, no city that I've been in had less than a few billion people.

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:34.320
[Guest]: And so in a way, you're thinking that you're comfortable with all of this.

00:47:34.320 --> 00:47:40.200
[Guest]: But at the same time, you're constantly reminded that this isn't the way you would go about

00:47:40.200 --> 00:47:44.920
[Guest]: doing things in the city, or that you're not happy with many of the outcomes that you see

00:47:44.920 --> 00:47:45.920
[Guest]: around you.

00:47:45.920 --> 00:47:51.560
[Guest]: And so you can start with simply no more than that as the motivation to get involved.

00:47:51.560 --> 00:47:57.280
[Guest]: And for a lot of people today, I think just making things better, whatever they mean by

00:47:57.280 --> 00:48:02.800
[Guest]: that phrase, making things better, not in a Trumpian way of let's make America great

00:48:02.800 --> 00:48:06.080
[Guest]: again, but really, actually make things better.

00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:14.800
[Guest]: A lot of people just get into public issues, primarily with that level of motivation for

00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:16.160
[Guest]: what they want to do.

00:48:16.160 --> 00:48:24.960
[Guest]: If we can create a way in which that can be persistent, and metric for continuous improvement,

00:48:24.960 --> 00:48:28.800
[Guest]: I think you would get a very large number of problem solving people from that you could

00:48:28.800 --> 00:48:29.800
[Guest]: do lots and lots of things.

00:48:29.800 --> 00:48:34.800
[Guest]: I actually think that if you did that, even governments would be responsive to that.

00:48:34.800 --> 00:48:41.080
[Guest]: I know I've worked closely with lots of people in government, both politicians and administrators.

00:48:41.080 --> 00:48:46.960
[Guest]: There is a genuine understanding, but they don't have enough allies for the things that

00:48:46.960 --> 00:48:49.880
[Guest]: you and I expect them to do.

00:48:49.880 --> 00:48:54.720
[Guest]: And so if you were to walk into a government department and offer to work with them to

00:48:54.720 --> 00:48:59.680
[Guest]: help do their jobs better, a very large number of people would welcome that.

00:48:59.680 --> 00:49:04.080
[Guest]: But if you walk into those same government departments and said, why the hell aren't

00:49:04.080 --> 00:49:10.960
[Guest]: you doing your job better, there is a reflexive defensiveness to that.

00:49:10.960 --> 00:49:12.880
[Guest]: So in a way, you need to be able to do both.

00:49:12.880 --> 00:49:16.840
[Guest]: You need to be able to go and say, these things aren't good enough.

00:49:16.840 --> 00:49:21.040
[Guest]: I expect them to be better, but I will also help you make them better.

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:26.920
[Guest]: I think if more of us can come to this balance, while on the one hand, expecting governments

00:49:26.920 --> 00:49:32.400
[Guest]: to do better, but on the other hand, accepting that we also have something to contribute

00:49:32.400 --> 00:49:39.360
[Guest]: to make that happen, I actually think that within 10 days, everyone in the city could

00:49:39.360 --> 00:49:43.920
[Guest]: see themselves becoming a stronger part of the life of their own neighborhood, at least,

00:49:43.920 --> 00:49:45.640
[Guest]: and start to make things better.

00:49:45.640 --> 00:49:46.640
[Guest]: It's very easy.

00:49:46.640 --> 00:49:51.440
[Guest]: It's like what I said earlier in the last conversation, how do you meet strangers?

00:49:51.440 --> 00:49:52.440
[Guest]: Just go out on the street.

00:49:52.440 --> 00:49:57.080
[Guest]: There are lots of strangers, walk up to one of them and say, hi, it sounds like a really

00:49:57.080 --> 00:50:02.520
[Guest]: bizarre thing to do, but it actually does get you to meet strangers if you did that.

00:50:02.520 --> 00:50:07.160
[Guest]: So in a way, you have to be sort of goal oriented in a lot of this stuff.

